PROJECT: BRIDLESTAY

Bridlestay is a production web/app platform that includes:
- Horse-friendly accommodation listings and bookings
- Route creation, following, comments, reviews, and maps
- Payments, fees, payouts, refunds, and support flows

This is a REAL-MONEY, SAFETY-ADJACENT product.

PROJECT PHILOSOPHY

- Reliability > speed
- Financial correctness is non-negotiable
- Auditability matters
- User trust is fragile
- Every feature must be usable end-to-end

You are not here to “just ship features”.
You are here to protect the product.

────────────────────────
CORE RULES
────────────────────────

1) ARCHITECTURE FIRST

Before writing code, you MUST:
- state which files/modules will change
- explain why those files exist
- explain how the change fits the current structure
- describe data flow (inputs → processing → outputs)

If structure is unclear, STOP and ask.

Avoid overengineering, deep inheritance, or magical abstractions.
Keep files single-purpose and functions short.

────────────────────────

2) ONE CHANGESET AT A TIME

Implement ONLY ONE small, well-defined change per response.

Do NOT:
- batch features
- sneak in refactors
- add “nice to haves”
- add future-proofing

If something else is needed, propose it separately.

────────────────────────

3) FULL FEATURE DELIVERY (NO HEADLESS FEATURES)

Any new feature, endpoint, or function MUST include:
- appropriate UI (screens/components/forms)
- integration into existing navigation or flows
- loading, error, and empty states
- input validation and user feedback
- permission/role handling where relevant
- an end-to-end user path that actually works

Do NOT implement backend-only features unless explicitly instructed.

If a feature cannot be completed end-to-end, STOP and propose the smallest usable slice that includes UI.

────────────────────────

4) NO INVENTED PRODUCT BEHAVIOR

You must NOT invent or modify:
- pricing
- fees
- commissions
- payouts
- refund rules
- business logic
- user roles

If any of these are unclear, STOP and ask.

────────────────────────

5) PAYMENTS & BOOKINGS (STRICT)

For anything touching payments or bookings:
- All money values MUST use integer minor units (pence)
- Currency must always be explicit
- NEVER use floating point for money
- Payment actions must be idempotent
- Never double-create bookings
- Never double-charge or double-refund
- Maintain a full audit trail (IDs, timestamps)

If unsure, STOP.

────────────────────────

6) SECURITY & PRIVACY

You must:
- validate and sanitise all inputs
- enforce least-privilege access
- never expose secrets
- never log PII or payment data
- consider abuse and fraud vectors

Call out risks explicitly.

────────────────────────

7) ROUTES & MAPS

Routes are safety-adjacent.

- Never imply legality or safety unless verified data exists
- Do not load large datasets in one go
- Prefer chunking, tiling, and lazy loading
- Separate route geometry from social metadata
- Be conscious of API usage costs

────────────────────────

8) DATA & DATABASE DISCIPLINE

If schema changes are required:
- propose the smallest possible change
- describe migration and rollback
- explain how existing data is handled
- NEVER delete data or fields without approval

Prefer additive changes only.

────────────────────────

9) PERFORMANCE & COST

- Avoid N+1 queries
- Avoid unnecessary recomputation
- Cache frequently-read data when appropriate
- Do NOT introduce background jobs without approval

────────────────────────

10) COMMENTS & NAMING

- Use clear, descriptive names
- Comment WHY, not just WHAT
- Every class, function, and non-trivial block must be commented
- Assume another developer will learn from the code

────────────────────────

11) STABLE FILE STRUCTURE

Once a file or folder purpose is defined:
- do not move or repurpose it
- do not reorganise without approval

────────────────────────

12) ASK WHEN UNCERTAIN

If anything is ambiguous, risky, or unclear:
STOP.
Ask.
Do not guess.

────────────────────────

13) CHANGELOG DISCIPLINE

After completing work in a session, update or create a changelog file:

Location: /changelogs/YYYY-MM-DD.md

Each changelog entry MUST include:
- Session summary (1-2 sentences)
- Files created, modified, or deleted
- What changed and WHY
- Risk notes if applicable
- Verification steps

Purpose: Auditability for the team (Richard + partner) to review changes.

If multiple sessions occur on the same day, append to the existing file with a time header.

────────────────────────
MANDATORY RESPONSE FORMAT
────────────────────────

Every response that changes code MUST end with:

A) CHANGE CHECKLIST
- [ ] Files created:
- [ ] Files modified:
- [ ] Files deleted:
- [ ] New functions/endpoints:
- [ ] UI added/updated:
- [ ] Schema changes/migrations:
- [ ] Config / ENV changes:
- [ ] Dependencies added/updated:
- [ ] User-facing behavior changes:
- [ ] Risk notes (payments/auth/data):
- [ ] Rollback steps:

B) VERIFICATION CHECKLIST
- [ ] Steps to test locally:
- [ ] Steps to test in staging:
- [ ] UI flow verified end-to-end:
- [ ] Edge cases tested:
- [ ] Logs/metrics to watch:

C) OPEN QUESTIONS / ASSUMPTIONS
- Explicitly list assumptions.
- Request confirmation if critical.

────────────────────────
GOLDEN RULE
────────────────────────

If the change does not make Bridlestay:
- safer
- clearer
- more correct

Then STOP and revise.
